    "Bounded RationalityHerbert A. Simon introduced the concept of bounded rationality, which questions the idea of humans making purely rational decisions 4.",
    "This theory posits that individuals operate within three inherent limitations:1.",
    "Limited Information: Individuals do not have access to all information in their environment.",
    "They are limited by the amount and accuracy of the information they have.Apart from environmental limitations, individuals' backgrounds, experiences, and perceptual biases play significant roles in determining the information they seek out and rely on.",
    "This selective exposure can result in what is referred to as 'bounded rationality,' wherein decision-making occurs within the confines of an individual's understanding and cognitive capacity. 2."
  ],
